9.2.1 Core Principle
Confidence describes interpretive clarity, not outcome probability.
Confidence must never imply:
• Likelihood of payout
• Likelihood of approval
• Probability of denial
• Legal enforceability
• Administrative behavior
Confidence reflects only:
• Clause alignment clarity
• Documentation completeness
• Causality clarity
• Structural conflict presence

9.2.2 Confidence Label Set (Canonical Enum)
All interpretive outputs must include one of the following structured labels:
HIGH_STRUCTURAL_ALIGNMENT
CONDITIONAL_ALIGNMENT
AMBIGUOUS_INTERPRETATION
DOCUMENTATION_INCOMPLETE
CONFLICT_PRESENT
INSUFFICIENT_DATA
Enum list must be versioned under 9.2.
No ad-hoc labels permitted.

9.2.3 Label Definitions
HIGH_STRUCTURAL_ALIGNMENT
Used when:
• Clause language clearly matches recorded facts
• No exclusion detected in reviewed sections
• Causality classification aligns
• No structural conflict identified
Plain-language rendering (UI-level formatting handled by 7.2):
“This aligns with the stated criteria under the reviewed sections.”
Must still include boundary statement (7.8.3).
SECTION 7.8 — DETERMINISTIC DEC…

CONDITIONAL_ALIGNMENT
Used when:
• Alignment exists
• Additional conditions must be met
• External review required
• Dependency clause present
Plain-language rendering:
“This aligns with the stated criteria, subject to the conditions described in the policy.”
No predictive framing permitted.

AMBIGUOUS_INTERPRETATION
Used when:
• Term undefined
• Clause historically interpreted inconsistently
• Secondary positioning conflict exists
• Language depends on administrative interpretation
Rendering:
“The relevant language is not defined in detail. Prior interpretations have varied.”
Must not say “unclear” or “we’re not sure.”

DOCUMENTATION_INCOMPLETE
Used when:
• Required timestamp missing
• CCO evidence classification insufficient
